{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_groomcreek_ver04/data/sn96060774/00414218258/1930123001/0232.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nflogaies International\nDevoted to the Interests ol Nogales and Vicinity\nPUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY AND FRIDAY MORN'xNU\nAt 225 Grand Ave., Nogales, Arizona\ni 1\nCRAIG POTTINGER Owner and Publisher\nRALPH RAWSTHORNE Business Manager\nSubscription Rate $4.00 A Year $2.50 Six Months, 45 cents a\nMaith.\nINTERNATIONAL PLATFORM\nBetter Drainage To Make Floods Impossible More Conventions\nMore Tourists\nA Law To Prohibit Jaywalking A Greater Nogaies\nA Motorcycle Road Patrol To Regulate Traffic On the Nogales-\nTucson Road Development Os Mining And Agricultural Re\nsources Os This District.\nEntered as second class matter February 3, 1928 at the\nI postoffice at Nogales, Arizona, under the Act of March 3. 1879.\n\nThe Turn Os The Year\nWhat will 1931 bring?\nThe year just ending will go down in history as\none of the hard years, economically speaking. Every\nbody in the United States has felt the pinch, not of\npoverty but of \u201chard times\u201d. Business has been slack,\nmoney hard to collect, credits have been curtailed,\nspending has been less, more people have been out of\nwork, than at any time since the last great depression,\nwhich lasted through the year 1921.\nYet there was little actual suffering in 1930, and\nthe great majority of people continued to drive their\nautomobiles, to enjoy themselves in much the same\nway as they were in the habit of doing. Most of us\ndidn\u2019t buy as many new clothes, but nearly all of us\nhad just as much of the same sort of things to eat.\nAccording to those who study those things, more of us\nwent to the movies in 1930 than in 1929. And when the\ncalls came for help for the unemployed, we gave more\nmoney, in hard cash, for charitable purposes, than we\nhad given in any year since the war, when everybody\nwas \u201cgiving till it hurt.\u201d\nIn short, \u201chard times\u201d as we have experienced\nthem in 1930, would have seemed like very good times\nindeed to the great majority of American, if .we had\nnot had six years of such riotous prosperity just be\nfore as to distort our sence of values.\nNobody can foretell the future, but we doubt very\nmuch whether 1931 will come any closer to the old fa\nshioned sort of \u201chard times\u201d with great masses of\npeople everywhere reduced to beggary and starvation.\nAll of the signs visible today point the other way. We\nknow that in many lines business is getting better; we\nare told that it is improving in almost every direction.\nThe principal thing the matter with our economic sit\nuation today is the habit of thinking in terms of hard\ntimes, which may take the better part of 1931 to over\ncome.\nIn the long run, however, one thing is certain.\nThe United States of America will go ahead toward\nbetter and brighter times than we have ever known.\nTo believe otherwise is to believe that the human race\nis going backward, and that is definitely not true.\no o o\nNew Year\u2019s Day\nFestivals in celebration of the beginning of a new\nyear have been traced back as far as 3000 B. C., to\nancient Babylon. They may have been held long before\nthat. Throughout the ages various peoples have ob\nserved various days as New Year\u2019s Day.\nIn view of the many calendars which have been\nemployed to mark the passage of time, much confu\nsion has resulted. Different peoples have counted the\nPINKY DINKY THE BOYS played SAFE By Terry Gilkison\nIff WELL, WELL, 80V 5.' YOU'RE -AMP HOPE VOU DION\u2019 T A'jK\nI! BACK PROM THE, OAR.ISTMA* p FOR A }\u00a3CONO PIECE\nI PARTY. OIP VOU HAVE A C 1 OF cAKc 010\nk you?\n.\\-rwo piece* the ff j J INGLE*,/\nV TIME Hi\n\"you KICK. AND sell An RAia\nI VMHEM YOU'RE MA.D,-'I'OU 00.\nWHEN YOUR DAP,'* AROUN^\nYOU'RE VERV.VERV N \u00bbCE-ARt YOU,\nyears from some real or imaginary event, and the\nlength of the year itself has varied according to the\ncalendar used.\nThe Mohammedan year, for example, is governed\nby the moon, instead of the sun, and consists of 12\nlunar months, or only 354 days. The Hebrew calendar\nalso consists of 354 days ordinarily, but an extra\nmonth is inserted once in 19 years, making 384 days in\nthese embolismic years, as they are called.\nThe ancient Egyptians year had 12 months of 30\ndays each, but five suplementary days were added at\nthe end, making 365 days. Similar peculiarities mark\ned the year of various other peoples. At one time or\nanother every day in the year has been considerd\nNew Year\u2019s Day according to some calendar or other.\nOur present calendar is a modification of that\nestablished by Julius Caesar in the year 46 B. C. Au\ngustus made some rearrangement of the number of\ndays in the various months, so that August, named\nfor him, might have as many days as July, named for\nJulius, for originally August had only 30 days. The\ncalendar we now use was established by Pope Gregory\nin 1582.\nSo, when we observe New Year\u2019s Day we may\nunderstand that it does not mean anything in par\nticular, except that it is the first day of a year arbi\ntrarily established as a convenient means of reckon\ning the flight of time.\n-o\u2014o\u2014o\u2014\nReturning\nAnnouncement made Friday that the Southern\nPacific railroad in January will place all shop workers\nin the company\u2019s locomotive and car departments now\nworking on a part time basis back on a full time\nschedule, is a further indication that the new year will\nbring a return of good times.\nThere are many other signs that the new year\nwill see a return of prosperity and that throughout\nthe United States business conditions will gradually\nimprove.\nThe busines depression has now been going on\nmore than a year and a much longer time than any\nformer depression in this country.\nThat prosperity is just around the corner and\nthat this nation is on the eve of the best period in its\nhistory is the concensus of opinion of business leaders.\nNineteen thirty one promises to be one of the\nmost propserous years ever known in the United\nStates.\nNogales is one of the best business towns in the\nsouthwest. This city is never hard hit by a depression.\nNot all Nogales business concerns show a loss\nthis year. We know of several that show a substantial\ngain.\nPENNEY CHRISTMAS BONUS\nFUND $536,770 THIS YEAR\nThe Annual Christmas Bonus\nFund for employees of the J. C.\nPenney Co., total $536,778.36 for 1930\nwith 6671 salespeople and other em\nployees benefitting. Distribution of\nthe bonus checks will be made at\nthe close of business on December\n24th.\nThe total number of employees\nbenefitted by this bonus is 144 great\ner than last year when the total re\ncipients of bonus checks totalled\n5527.\nBonus checks are based upon dur\nation of service with the company\nand the annual salary rate of the\nindividual. In all, employees in more\nthan 1450 stores as well as in the\nNew York City and St. Louis dis\ntrict offices will receive checks on\nChristmas Eve.\nAll associates sharing in this bon\nus were in the employ of the com\npany on January Ist, 1930.\nTen employees of the local J. C.\nPenndy Co. store participated in\nNOGALES INTERNATIONAL\nthe bonuses given by the company\nthis year according to R. S. Burns,\nmanager. Maximum bonuses for\nlength of service went to Mrs. Mar\ngarita Gardner. The woman em\nployee receiving the largest bonus\nfor sales volume was Miss Lola\nYnigo. Other participants in bonus\nchecks were: Mrs. J. Griffith, Miss\nAnselma Abascal, Miss Flora Del-'\ngado, Miss D. Goyeneche, Miss Lu- 1\nisa Mazon, Miss Isabel Abascal, j\nMiss Norah O'Donnell and Mrs. Na-\ntalia Bennett.\nGolf Turney In\nSemi Final Stag es\ni\nThe winter tournament at the No-!\ngales Golf Club entered the semi-1\nfinal stages Sunday with some sen\nsational matches taking place. The\nfeature match of the day also prov\ned the biggest upset when A1 Faught\ntook the measure of J. F. Johnson\nand defeated the latter 1 up. In the\nother bracket it took Newton Mer\ncer 20 holes to dispose of W. H. Dav\ney. In the second flight it took Ro\nbert Burns 19 holes to defeat W. J.\nMcGregor.\nResults of matches played Sunday\nfollow:\nFIRST FLIGHT\nA1 Faught won from J. F. John\nson 1 up.\nNewton Mercer won from W. H.\nDavey 1 up in 20 holes.\nSECOND FLIGHT\nRobert Burns won from W. J.\nMcGregor 1 up in 19 holes.\nTHIRD FLIGHT\nJoe Bracker won from F. J. B.\nGonzalez 1 up.\nSam Bracker w r on from Julio Pina\n4 up and 2 to go.\nFOURTH FLIGHT\nN. Batsell won from A. Gillespie,\nSr., 4 up and 3 to go.\nF. Mexia won from E. Alvarez by\ndefault.\nj The pairing for the final matches\n,to be played Sunday, January 4th,\nj 1931, follow:\nFIRST FLIGHT\nA1 Faught versus Newton Mercer.\nSECOND FLIGHT\nRobert Burns versus winner of\nW. H. Davey, Jr., and R. Aguilar\nmatch.\nTHIRD FLIGHT\nJoe Bracker versus Sam Bracker.\nFOURTH FLIGHT\nN. Batsell versus F. Mexia.\nHtomorrcwL\nFRANK PARKER 'l\nSTOCKBMMiE\nCHOCOLATE\nPerhaps America\u2019s most widely-dis\ntributed food product is chocolate. It\nwas unknown to the civilized world\nuntil the Spanish conquistadores found\nthe Mexicans drinking a decoction\nmade from the cacao bean. The ex\nplorers took the bean and the drink\nback to Europe with them.\nWe use about 150,000,000 pounds of\nchocolate a year, in the form of candy,\nflavoring for ice-cream and soda, and\nas a drink, which we call cocoa, al\nthough the original Mexican word was\ncacao. The rest of the world uses\nabout as much as we do.\nThe food value of chocolate is high;\nit is a concentrated energy producer.\nThe forms in which it is generally sold,\nhighly sweetened, make it less digest\nible for persons who cannot take care\nof sweets easily. But for anybody en\ngaged in active physical work there is\nno better stimulant combined with\nnourishment than sweetened chocolate.\n\nUNEMPLOYMENT\nWhile the rest of the country is re\ncovering its normal tone quite notice\nably, New York City is getting very\nsorry for itself over the business de\npression and unemployment. Business\nisn\u2019t any worse in New York than it\nis anywhere else, and there are no\nmore unemployed, proportionately,\nthan in any other town. But the city\nnewspapers and the public have just\ngot around to taking serious notice\nand to raising money for the benefit\nof the unemployed. It has become the\nfashionable thing for the smart set to\nattend football games for charity, join\nunemployment committees and get\ntheir names and pictures in the paper.\nSeveral million dollars has been raised,\nwith the result that every tramp and\ndrifter in the country is heading for\nNew York as fast as he can go, to get\nsome of the easy money that is being\nhanded out to anybody who can pull a\npoor face.\nNot that there isn\u2019t unemployment\nand suffering, too, in New York. It\nis mostly in cases where illness, old\nage or sheer incompetence is to blame.\nI know of many cases where people\nlooking for competent help have been\nunable to find any really useful persons\nwho didn\u2019t have a job.\n\nHOGS\nThere is something in the idea of\nfeeding wheat instead of corn to live\nstock, according to an account issued\nby the Federal Farm Board of the ex\nperiences of many farmers who have\ntried it.\nFrank Evans of Oklahoma fed 311\nhogs on wheat, and found that 400\npounds of wheat made 100 pounds of\npork. He figured up what he got for\nliis wheat thus converted into pork,\nand says it brought him $1.67 a bushel.\nOther farmers who have tried the\nsame thing report that wheat has\nbrought them from $1 to $1.50 a bushel\nby the same process.\nEvery innovation of this sort is a\nstep toward the ultimate solution of the\nfarm problem.\n\nDOLLARS\nTo most of us a dollar is just a\ndollar. To financial experts, a dollar\nis merely a gauge whereby commodities\nire rneasured. But financiers often\nPALACE BARBER\nSHOP\nN. E. CRENSHAW, Prop.\nAll union barbers \u2014Best paid\nworkmen\nBarberia Con Tres Viejoa\n245 Morley Ave.\nSANTA\"CRUZ\nCOUNTY\nCompany\nF. A. French, Manager\nAbstract Title\nCourthouse\nPhone S 5\nThirst Quenching Drinks\nThat Hit The Spot\nCooling, Refreshing and Luscious\nOICmIKE AYUP, Prop.\nNogales, Sonora\nhigiT grade\nREFRESHMENTS\nAt Moderate Prices\nCURB SERVICE\nNOGALES, ARIZ., TUESDAY, DEC. 30. 1930\nspeak of the dollar as if it were vari\nable, while commodities are stationary.\nInstead of saying, for example, that\nwheat is cheaper, they will say that the\nwheat dollar is higher.\nDr. Andrew A. Bock, famous statis\ntician, says that the \u201cwholesale dollar\u2019\u2019\nhas increased about 7 percent and the\n\u201ccost-of-living\u2019\u2019 dollar about per\ncent since the beginning of 1930. Thai\nis merely another way of saying that\nwholesale prices are down below last\nyear\u2019s level and that retail prices for\nthe necessities of life are down almost\nas much. The interesting point he\nmakes is that while the \u201cwages dollar\"\nhas also increased, \u2014another way of\nsaying that wages on the average are\nlower\u2014the shrinkage there is only 3'/j\npercent so that there is really a larger\nmargin above living costs, for the man\nwho has a job, than there was a year\nago for the man on the same wages.\n\nBARTON\nThe Rev. William E. Barton, who\ndied the other day, will be remembered\na hundred years from now not because\nhe was a great preacher, which he was,\nbut because he did more than any other\nperson to dig out all of the facts\nabout the life and ancestry of Abra\nham Lincoln.\nUntil Dr. Barton began his research,\nmany of the popular beliefs about Lin\ncoln were pure myth. His friends had\nwritten accounts of his life which were\nas false in many particulars as those\nwritten by enemies. Dr. Barton\u2019s\nseveral books revealed Lincoln as he\nreally was, and settled forever the\nquestion of his ancestry and paternity\nWhile engaged in this work-, L?\nBarton was at the same time pastor cd\none of the most famous churches h\nthe country, the Oak Park Congrega\ntional. which he built up into a mode\u2019\nfor all \u201cinstitutional\u201d churches. He\nwas a great and good man and the\nfather of a son, Bruce Barton, who is\nas famous in his line as the minister\nwas.\nFOR RENT: Room with outside\nentrance. Inquire Mrs. Tolley, 520 W.\n(Pub. 11-28\u201412-2)\nWANTED\u2014To borrow SI,OOO on\nhundred acres and house. Edward\nL. Sierras, Tubac, Ariz. (11-25 ts)\nA BARGAIN Buescher True-\nTone C-Melody Saxophone. Silver\nPlated-Gold Bell. In Good Condi\ntion. Excellent instrument for be\nginning student. $25.00 cash. Apply\nat Nogales International.\n(11-14 ts)\nFOR SALE A refrigerator, in\ngood shape. Phone 678.\n(11-14 ts)\nWould trade Buick Auto valued\nat S3OO for city lot. C. C. Crenshaw,\n215 Grand Avenue. (10-24 ts)\n\"\"EPILEPSY CURABLE? Detroit\nlady finds complete relief for hus\nband. Specialists home and abroad\nfailed. Nothing to sell. All letters an\nswered. Mrs. Geo. Dempster, Apt.\nK 5, 6900 LaFayette Blvd. West, De\ntroit, Mich.\n(9-12 ts)\nNew Fashion\nTailors\n238 GRAND\nPHONE 179-W\nCleaning and\nPressing\nMending and Alterations\nPrices Reasonable\nWork Guaranteed\nWe Call For and Deliver\nOne-Day Service\nSOUTHWEST\nFREIGHT LINES\nNOGALES PATAGONIA\nDaily Service\nNogales Office, 446 Grand Ave.\nPhone 22\nMILLER\u2019S ASSAY\nOFFICE\nEstablished 1913\nHUGO W. MILLER\nAssayers\u2014Ore Bullion Buyers\nRegistered Assayer\u2014Mining\nEngineer\nBox 257 Nogales, Arizona\n~west coasF\nPRODUCE CO. j\nIMPORTERS EXPORTERS j\nWHOLESALE\nVegetables, Fruits\nProduce\nBox 366 Phone 11 1\nMviLSofsH\nj BAKERY\nBuy Home\nProducts\nYour Home Baker j\n220 Grand Ave.\nI Phone 201\nWELDING\nWe weld anything that\nMelts. All Welding\nGuaranteed.\ndetroiFradiator\nAND BODY WORKS\nI. G. Ibach, Prop.\n438 Grand Ave.\nNogales. Ariz.\n1\nGOOD NEWS TO SUFFERERS j\nSCIATICA, LUMBAGO\nNEURALGIA GOUT\nMen and women, young and\nold, suffering from the most ex\ncruciating attacks of rheuma\ntism, having tried all that is\nknown to medical science to find\nrelief, have now been cured in\nmany remarkable ways with RU\nPROTEC. This new discovery is\nthe great Rheumatism remedy of\nthe century.\nWe guarantee that you will\nbe completely satisfied, relieved,\nand your rheumatism gone, or\nback goes your money. Price\nSI.OO a package.\nSOLD AT ALL DRUG STORES\nL\nj SAME PRESCRIPTION\nHE WROTE IN 1892 j\nWhen Dr. Caldwell started to practio*\nmedicine, back in 1875, the needs for a\nlaxative were not as great as today.\nPeople lived normal lives, ate plain,\nwholesome food, and got plenty of fresh\nair. But even that early there were\nIrastic physics and purges* for the relief\n>f constipation which Dr. Caldwell did\naot believe were good for human beings.\nThe prescription for constipation that\nle used early in his practice, and which\nle nut in drug stores in 1892 under the\nlame of Dr. Caldwell\u2019s Syrup Pepsin,\n3 a liquid vegetable remedy, intended\nor women, children and elderly people,\nind they need just such a mild, safe\n>owel stimulant.\nThis prescription has proven its worth\nmd is now the largest selling liquid\naxative. It has won the confidence of\nicople who needed it to get relief from\nleadaches, biliousness, tlatulence, indi\n\u25a0estion, loss of appetite and sleep, bad\nleath, dyspepsia, colds, fevers. At your\niraggist,\" or write \u201cSyrup Pepsin,\u201d\nJept. 88, Monticello, Illinois, for free\nrial bottle.","height":"25176","width":"17976"}}
